WEBVTT

00:00:01.120 --> 00:00:06.000
<v Speaker 1>Let's look again at how we speak about the future in Spanish.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:10.880
<v Speaker 1>We saw that we have a future tense, but we might not use it very often

00:00:11.019 --> 00:00:18.779
<v Speaker 1>because firstly we can just use the present to talk about the future if we have some future context

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:31.080
<v Speaker 1>Some word like manyana, tomorrow, later, mas tarde, or even another part of the sentence which shows us that we're talking about the future, we can just use the present.

00:00:31.020 --> 00:00:36.940
<v Speaker 1>When we don't have that, we can use IR-a to go to.

00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:41.260
<v Speaker 1>So boya, bamosa, basa.

00:00:41.140 --> 00:00:43.060
<v Speaker 1>Which is also present tense.

00:00:43.060 --> 00:00:45.380
<v Speaker 1>Boy, bas vamos, it's present.

00:00:45.380 --> 00:00:48.740
<v Speaker 1>But we can use it to talk about the future.

00:00:48.740 --> 00:00:51.620
<v Speaker 1>So for example, bailar

00:00:52.020 --> 00:00:56.740
<v Speaker 1>Bailar, B-A-I-L-A-R, means to dance.

00:00:56.740 --> 00:00:59.940
<v Speaker 1>We can relate it to Ballerina

00:01:00.060 --> 00:01:03.980
<v Speaker 1>Ballerina actually is just dancer in Spanish.

00:01:03.980 --> 00:01:06.140
<v Speaker 1>Bailarin in Spanish is dancer.

00:01:06.140 --> 00:01:10.620
<v Speaker 1>So that's where we get ballerina from bailar.

00:01:10.620 --> 00:01:14.860
<v Speaker 1>So if you want to say we are going to dance.

00:01:14.860 --> 00:01:16.460
<v Speaker 2>Vamos a bailar.

00:01:16.460 --> 00:01:17.900
<v Speaker 1>Vamos a bailar.

00:01:17.900 --> 00:01:18.620
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:28.700
<v Speaker 1>If you had some future context like later, más tarde, or literally more late, you could just say we dance later.

00:01:30.260 --> 00:01:31.860
<v Speaker 2>Bailamos más tarde.

00:01:31.860 --> 00:01:32.180
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:01:32.180 --> 00:01:34.340
<v Speaker 1>Bailamos más tarde.

00:01:34.340 --> 00:01:38.580
<v Speaker 1>But you could have used that structure with Vamos if you wanted to.

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:40.180
<v Speaker 1>You have the option.

00:01:39.740 --> 00:01:46.700
<v Speaker 1>We can say bailamos más tarde, or we could say we're going to dance later.

00:01:46.700 --> 00:01:49.100
<v Speaker 2>Vamos a bailar mas tarde.

00:01:49.100 --> 00:01:49.740
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:01:49.740 --> 00:01:51.900
<v Speaker 1>Vamos a bailar mas tarde.

00:01:52.140 --> 00:01:54.300
<v Speaker 1>So we saw that we have a future tense.

00:01:54.460 --> 00:02:02.940
<v Speaker 1>We have a future tense, although we might not need to use it very often because we have this situation in Spanish that we can use the present or that

00:02:03.140 --> 00:02:11.940
<v Speaker 1>IRA to go to is used even more often than in English this structure of I'm going to do it

00:02:11.860 --> 00:02:16.020
<v Speaker 1>instead of I'll do it is used even more in Spanish than in English.

00:02:16.020 --> 00:02:17.940
<v Speaker 1>But we do have a future tense.

00:02:17.940 --> 00:02:24.019
<v Speaker 1>And the future tense is luckily very related to the different versions

00:02:24.420 --> 00:02:27.860
<v Speaker 1>that we found of the verb aber.

00:02:27.860 --> 00:02:33.540
<v Speaker 1>Aber was a very irregular verb, this to have, that we used to go into the past.

00:02:33.540 --> 00:02:35.540
<v Speaker 1>What was the trick that we used

00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:42.060
<v Speaker 1>to find the different versions of this very irregular verb aber.

00:02:42.220 --> 00:02:45.420
<v Speaker 2>And we use the vowels, the e and a.

00:02:45.660 --> 00:02:45.900
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:46.640 --> 00:02:48.720
<v Speaker 1>We use these to take off from.

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:52.400
<v Speaker 1>We go what are the two vowels in Aber E and A?

00:02:52.400 --> 00:02:53.040
<v Speaker 1>Okay.

00:02:53.040 --> 00:02:57.519
<v Speaker 1>E by itself means I have.

00:02:57.519 --> 00:03:01.360
<v Speaker 1>I have and a by itself means.

00:03:01.400 --> 00:03:05.480
<v Speaker 2>He, she, it, or you formal have.

00:03:05.480 --> 00:03:06.200
<v Speaker 1>Perfect.

00:03:06.200 --> 00:03:09.080
<v Speaker 1>And from these we can find the other versions.

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:13.880
<v Speaker 1>So we have if I have and uh we have is

00:03:15.340 --> 00:03:16.140
<v Speaker 1>EMOS.

00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:19.819
<v Speaker 1>And we have A for he, she, it, U formal.

00:03:20.060 --> 00:03:23.420
<v Speaker 1>For U informal, what would we do to A?

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:24.800
<v Speaker 1>Us.

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:25.680
<v Speaker 1>Us.

00:03:25.680 --> 00:03:27.040
<v Speaker 1>H A S.

00:03:27.040 --> 00:03:28.800
<v Speaker 1>Now completely silent this H.

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:32.080
<v Speaker 1>This H that we find in all of these forms.

00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:34.160
<v Speaker 1>They have or you guys have

00:03:35.160 --> 00:03:35.800
<v Speaker 2>An.

00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:36.280
<v Speaker 1>An.

00:03:36.280 --> 00:03:38.920
<v Speaker 1>So these are our different versions of Aber.

00:03:38.920 --> 00:03:44.440
<v Speaker 1>Now these very sounds, so the sounds, because we're not including the H

00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:54.959
<v Speaker 1>the sounds e-emos a as an are the same sounds that we add onto the two form of the verb to get this future tense

00:03:55.220 --> 00:03:58.659
<v Speaker 1>So we have a verb like bailar to dance.

00:03:58.659 --> 00:04:02.819
<v Speaker 1>If I want to say I will dance using this future tense

00:04:02.940 --> 00:04:06.140
<v Speaker 1>I can look at how is I have from aber.

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:07.980
<v Speaker 1>So how is I have from aber.

00:04:08.860 --> 00:04:11.340
<v Speaker 1>And I can just stick it on the end.

00:04:11.340 --> 00:04:13.260
<v Speaker 1>But it's the sound that is the same.

00:04:13.260 --> 00:04:15.980
<v Speaker 1>We are what we are sticking on the end of the verb is an e

00:04:16.239 --> 00:04:18.640
<v Speaker 1>Ah, not the H E.

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:21.680
<v Speaker 1>So I will dance.

00:04:21.680 --> 00:04:24.800
<v Speaker 2>Is it bailare or bailare?

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:33.240
<v Speaker 1>The ending takes the accent and we said that in Spanish we are pushing the accent into the future, which is an interesting phenomenon.

00:04:33.240 --> 00:04:38.360
<v Speaker 1>We spoke about how in Greek, for example, in the past you pull it back into the past

00:04:38.639 --> 00:04:41.919
<v Speaker 1>So we find this phenomenon occurring in other languages as well.

00:04:41.919 --> 00:04:48.240
<v Speaker 1>Here we are literally pushing the accent into the future and we accent that ending and we say bailare.

00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:49.520
<v Speaker 1>Bailare.

00:04:49.520 --> 00:04:51.360
<v Speaker 1>I will dance.

00:04:51.360 --> 00:04:52.880
<v Speaker 1>We will dance.

00:04:53.820 --> 00:04:54.780
<v Speaker 2>Bailaremos.

00:04:54.780 --> 00:04:55.740
<v Speaker 1>Bailaremos.

00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:59.580
<v Speaker 1>He, she, it, you fummel will dance.

00:04:59.580 --> 00:05:00.460
<v Speaker 2>Bailará.

00:05:00.460 --> 00:05:01.100
<v Speaker 1>Bailará.

00:05:01.100 --> 00:05:03.420
<v Speaker 1>They or you guys will dance.

